Q7¶

Imputation: is the process of replacing missing values with a substitution.

One such technique is mean imputation, where missing values are replaced by the mean value of the non-missing data. Similarly, the median and mode of the non-missing data could be used as a substitute. Alternatively, missing values could be replaced with the value of the previous or the next value or simply put a random value into the data.

  • Substitution with Mean:
    Using the average to fill missing values is simple to do and the mean is a good representation of the data. But sometimes it is impossible to use this for a column.
  • Substitution with Median:
    The outlier data can affect the mean negatively. So the median can be a good alternative in such cases.
  • Substitution with Mode:
    Mean and median do not work with categorical data. Using the mode can be a alternative for such data.
  • Random Substitution:
    In this method we fill using random values, mostly in the range of the column's minimum and maximum data, or between the categories.
  • Forward-fill and Backward-fill:
    In this method we fill the missing values with next or previous quantity.

A more advanced approach is an imputation method using model-based techniques, such as k-NN imputation or MICE (Multiple Imputation by Chained Equations). While the former fills the missing data based on the k nearest neighbors, the latter fits the observed data into a regression model before imputing missing values.

Dropping: Another option is to remove any observations that contain missing values. There are two main ways for this:

  • Dropping Columns:
    In this method we remove any column that has missing values. This method should only be considered on columns that have too many missing values Or we use a lot of data.
  • Dropping Rows:
    Works similarly to dropping columns.
    If we remove all rows that have missing values, if a column is all missing, then all of the rows will be gone.
    This method should also only be considered on rows that have most of their properties missing.

Finally, in some cases where missing data is limited, one could choose to ignore these values altogether and proceed with the analysis.

Q9¶

Normalization is a technique used to standardize the range of values of numerical features in a dataset. It is a common preprocessing step in machine learning and data analysis to ensure that different features are on a similar scale, which can help improve the performance of certain algorithms. For example, we can scale the values of the features to the range of [0, 1] or [-1, 1]. This method is useful when we have no outliers and the data lies in a fixed range. We can use the MinMaxScaler method to do this. Below is the formula for the MinMaxScaler method:

$$X_{norm} = \frac{X - X_{min}}{X_{max} - X_{min}}$$

Normalization is a good technique to use when you do not know the distribution of your data or when you know the distribution is not Gaussian. Normalization is useful when your data has varying scales and the algorithm you are using does not make assumptions about the distribution of your data.

Standardization is a technique used to transform numerical data to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. We can use the StandardScaler method to do this. Below is the formula for the StandardScaler method:

$$X_{std} = \frac{X - \mu}{\sigma}$$

Standardization assumes that your data has a Gaussian distribution. This does not strictly have to be true, but the technique is more effective if your attribute distribution is Gaussian. Standardization is useful when your data has varying scales and the algorithm you are using does make assumptions about your data having a Gaussian distribution, such as linear regression, logistic regression, and linear discriminant analysis.

Now lets see which of the standardization and normalization we need.

In [ ]:
df.hist(bins=20, figsize=(20,15))

Since the features with the most correlation are a bit away from Gaussian distribution we use normalization. we also use standardization because it causes our ML models to converge easier.

Here we define the Scaler class which can do the standardization and normalization.

In [ ]:
class Scaler:
    def __init__(self, df):
        self.df = df
        self.numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include="number")
        self.std = StandardScaler()
        self.norm = MinMaxScaler()

    def standardization(self, exclude_cols):
        self.df[self.numeric_cols.columns] = self.std.fit_transform(self.numeric_cols)
        self.df[exclude_cols] = self.numeric_cols[exclude_cols]

    def normalization(self, exclude_cols):
        self.df[self.numeric_cols.columns] = self.norm.fit_transform(self.numeric_cols)
        self.df[exclude_cols] = self.numeric_cols[exclude_cols]

Q10¶

There are many ways to encode the categorical features. Some of them are as follows:

  • One-Hot Encoding: This method creates binary columns for each category in a categorical feature. Each column represents the presence or absence of a specific category, and only one column can have a value of 1 for each sample.

  • Label Encoding: Label encoding assigns a unique integer value to each category in a categorical feature. Each category is mapped to a numerical label, allowing the model to understand the ordinal relationship between categories.

  • Ordinal Encoding: Similar to label encoding, ordinal encoding assigns numerical labels to categories. However, in ordinal encoding, the labels are assigned based on the order or rank of the categories.

  • Count Encoding: Count encoding replaces each category with the count of occurrences of that category in the dataset. It encodes categories based on their frequency and can be useful when the frequency of categories carries important information.

  • Target Encoding: Target encoding replaces each category with the mean of the target variable for that category.

  • Frequency Encoding: Frequency encoding replaces each category with the frequency or proportion of that category in the dataset.

  • Binary Encoding: Binary encoding represents each category with binary digits. Each category is first assigned an ordinal label, which is then converted into binary representation. Binary encoding reduces the dimensionality compared to one-hot encoding while preserving some information about the categories.

  • Hash Encoding: Hash encoding applies a hashing function to map categories to a fixed number of values. It reduces the dimensionality of the feature space but may introduce collisions.

  • Text Encoding: Categorical features are often stored as text. Before using them in model training, you can convert these texts into numerical representations such as TF-IDF vectors or Word2Vec embeddings.

Here for encoding we use Label Encoding as I don't want to increase the dimensions of the dataset.

Q12¶

There are some ways to split the dataset into train and test sets. Some of them are as follows:

  • Holdout Method: In this method, a percentage of the data, is randomly assigned to the training set, and the remaining percentage is allocated to the test set.

  • Cross-Validation: Cross-validation is a technique where the data is divided into multiple subsets or folds. The model is trained and evaluated multiple times, with each fold used as the test set once and the rest as the training set.

    • K-Fold Cross-Validation: The data is divided into K subsets of approximately equal size. The model is trained and evaluated K times, with each fold used as the test set once. The final performance is averaged over the K iterations.

    • Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation: This method is similar to K-Fold, but it ensures that the distribution of target classes remains consistent across each fold. This is particularly useful when dealing with imbalanced datasets.

  • Leave-One-Out Cross-Validation: Here, each data point is used as the test set, and the rest of the data is used for training. This method is computationally expensive for large datasets but can provide an unbiased evaluation.

  • Time-based Split: This method is useful when we have a time series dataset. But it is not useful in this case.

Q13¶

Validation data in machine learning is a subset of labeled data that is used to evaluate the performance of a trained model. It helps in adjusting model settings to improve generalization and prevent overfitting. The data should be representative of real-world scenarios and is separate from the training and test data.

Q14¶

The process works as follows:

  • The data is divided into k equal-sized subsets.
  • The model is trained k times, each time using k-1 folds as training data and one fold as validation data.
  • The performance of the model is evaluated on the validation set for each iteration.
  • The final performance metric is usually an average of the performance across all k iterations.

K-fold cross-validation provides a more robust estimate of a model's performance compared to a single train-validation split. It helps to ensure that the model's evaluation is not dependent on a specific random split of the data, as it evaluates the model on different subsets of the data.

Q15¶

Main form of simple linear regression function: $$f(x) = \alpha x + \beta$$

here we want to find the intercept($\alpha$) and slope($\beta$) by minimizing the derivation of the RSS function:

  • step 1: Compute RSS of the training data

$$ RSS = \Sigma (y_i - (\hat{\beta} + \hat{\alpha} * x_i) )^2 $$

Where $\hat{\alpha}$ is the estimated value of the constant term $\alpha$ and $\hat{\beta}$ is the estimated value of the slope coefficient $\beta$

  • step 2: Compute the derivatives of the RSS function in term of $\underline{\alpha}$ and $\underline{\beta}$, and set them equal to 0 to find the desired parameters

$$ \frac{\partial RSS}{\partial \beta} = \Sigma (-f(x_i) + \hat{\beta} + \hat{\alpha} * x_i) = 0$$ $$ \to \hat{\beta} = \hat{y} - \hat{\alpha} \hat{x} \to (1)$$

$$ \frac{\partial RSS}{\partial \alpha} = \Sigma (-2 x_i y_i + 2 \hat{\beta} x_i + 2\hat{\alpha} x_i ^ 2) = 0 \to (2)$$

$$ (1) , (2) \to \hat{\alpha} = \frac{\Sigma{(x_i - \hat{x})(y_i - \hat{y})}}{\Sigma{(x_i - \hat{x})^2}} $$ $$ \hat{\beta} = \hat{y} - \hat{\alpha} \hat{x}$$

In [ ]:
def simple_linear_regression(input_feature, output):
    Sxy = (input_feature * output).sum() - input_feature.sum() * output.sum() / len(output)
    Sxx = (input_feature ** 2).sum() - (input_feature.sum())**2 / len(output)
    slope = Sxy / Sxx
    intercept = output.mean() - slope * input_feature.mean()
    return (intercept, slope)

Now complete this get_regression_predictions(...) function to predict the value of given data based on the calculated intercept and slope

In [ ]:
def get_regression_predictions(input_feature, intercept, slope):
    return intercept + slope * input_feature

Q17¶

Residual Sum of Squares (RSS): The RSS is the sum of the squared differences between the predicted values and the actual values. It measures the total amount of error in the model.
Mean Squared Error (MSE): The MSE is the average of the squared differences between the predicted values and the actual values. It measures the average amount of error in the model.
Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): The RMSE is the square root of the MSE. It measures the average amount of error in the model in the same units as the dependent variable.
R-squared (R2) score: The R2 score is a measure of how well the model fits the data. It represents the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variables. The R2 score ranges from 0 to 1, with higher values indicating a better fit.
The R2 score is calculated by comparing the sum of the squared differences between the actual and predicted values of the dependent variable to the total sum of squared differences between the actual and mean values of the dependent variable. Matematically, the R2 score formula is shown as follows:



$$R^2 = 1 - \frac{SSres}{SStot} = 1 - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i,true} - y_{i,pred})^2}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_{i,true} - \bar{y}_{true})^2} $$

def get_root_mean_square_error(predicted_values, output):
    residuals = output - predicted_values

    residuals_squared_sum = np.sum(residuals ** 2)

    mean_residuals_squared = residuals_squared_sum / len(output)

    RMSE = np.sqrt(mean_residuals_squared)

    return RMSE
In [ ]:
def get_r2_score(predicted_values, output):
    residuals = output - predicted_values

    SSres = np.sum(residuals ** 2)

    SStot = np.sum((output - np.mean(output)) ** 2)

    R2_score = 1 - SSres / SStot

    return R2_score

2. Multiple Regression¶

Multiple regression is a statistical technique that aims to model the relationship between a dependent variable and two or more independent variables.

Multiple regression with n independent variables is expressed as follows:

$$f(x) = \beta _{0} + \beta_{1} x_{1} + \beta_{2} x_{2} + \beta_{3} x_{3} + \beta_{4} x_{4} + ... + \beta_{n} x_{n} + c $$

To optimize the model for accurate predictions, multiple regression commonly employs iterative algorithms such as gradient descent.

The main goal of the optimization process is to make our predictions as close as possible to the actual values. We measure the prediction error using a cost function, usually denoted as $J(\beta)$.

$$ J(\beta)= \frac {1}{2m} Σ_{i=0}^{m-1}(y_i - (\hat \beta _{0} + \hat \beta_{1} x_{1} + \hat \beta_{2} x_{2} + \hat \beta_{3} x_{3} + \hat \beta_{4} x_{4} + ... + \hat \beta_{n} x_{n}) )^2 $$

Gradient descent iteratively adjusts the coefficients $(\beta_i)$ to minimize the cost function. The update rule for each coefficient is:

$$\beta_{i} = \beta _ {i} - \alpha \frac {∂J(\beta)}{∂\beta_{i}}$$

$$ \frac {∂J(\beta)}{∂\beta_{i}} = \frac {1}{m}Σ_{j=0}^{m-1}(y_j - (\hat \beta _{0} + \hat \beta_{1} x_{j1} + \hat \beta_{2} x_{j2} + \hat \beta_{3} x_{j3} + \hat \beta_{4} x_{j4} + ... + \hat \beta_{n} x_{jn})) x_{ji} $$

Predicting output given regression weights¶

Based on the formula above and np.dot() method, complete this function to compute the predictions for an entire matrix of features given the matrix, bias, and the weights. Provide an explanation of np.dot method and the reasoning behind using this method in your code:

The dot product is a mathematical operation between two vectors that results in a scalar value. we can perform this operation in NumPy using np.dot(). for prediction we use this formula: $$\hat{Y} = X\beta + b$$ and because both $X$ and $\beta$ are vectors we use the np.dot.

In [ ]:
def predict_output(feature_matrix, weights, bias):
    prediction = np.dot(feature_matrix, weights)
    prediction += bias
    
    return prediction

Computing the Derivative¶

As we saw, the cost function is the sum over the data points of the squared difference between an observed output and a predicted output.

Since the derivative of a sum is the sum of the derivatives, we can compute the derivative for a single data point and then sum over data points. We can write the squared difference between the observed output and predicted output for a single point as follows:

$$ (output - (const* w _{0} + [feature_1] * w_{1} + ...+ [feature_n] * w_{n} ))^2 $$

With n feautures and a const , So the derivative will be :

$$ 2 * (output - (const* w _{0} + [feature_1] * w_{1} + ...+ [feature_n] * w_{n} )) $$

The term inside the paranethesis is just the error (difference between prediction and output). So we can re-write this as:

$$2 * error*[feature_i] $$

That is, the derivative for the weight for feature i is the sum (over data points) of 2 times the product of the error and the feature itself. In the case of the constant then this is just twice the sum of the errors!

Recall that twice the sum of the product of two vectors is just twice the dot product of the two vectors. Therefore the derivative for the weight for feature_i is just two times the dot product between the values of feature_i and the current errors.

With this in mind, complete the following derivative function which computes the derivative of the weight given the value of the feature (over all data points) and the errors (over all data points).

In [ ]:
def feature_derivative(errors, feature):
    feature_derivative = 2 * np.dot(errors, feature)
    return feature_derivative

Gradient Descent¶

Now we will write a function that performs a gradient descent. The basic premise is simple. Given a starting point we update the current weights by moving in the negative gradient direction. Recall that the gradient is the direction of increase and therefore the negative gradient is the direction of decrease and we're trying to minimize a cost function.

The amount by which we move in the negative gradient direction is called the 'step size'. We stop when we are 'sufficiently close' to the optimum. We define this by requiring that the magnitude (length) of the gradient vector to be smaller than a fixed 'tolerance'.

With this in mind, complete the following gradient descent function below using your derivative function above. For each step in the gradient descent we update the weight for each feature befofe computing our stopping criteria.

In [ ]:
def regression_gradient_descent(feature_matrix, outputs, initial_weights, bias, step_size, tolerance):
    weights = np.array(initial_weights)
    converged = False
    while not converged:
        predictions = predict_output(feature_matrix, weights, bias)
        errors = outputs - predictions

        gradient = - feature_derivative(feature_matrix.T, errors)
        weights -= step_size * gradient

        bias_gradient = -2 * np.sum(errors)
        bias -= step_size * bias_gradient

        if np.linalg.norm(gradient) < tolerance:
            converged = True

    return weights, bias

# Utility functions for multiple regression

def normalize_features(chosen_features, data_frame):
    for feature in chosen_features:
        data_frame[feature] = (data_frame[feature] - data_frame[feature].mean()) / data_frame[feature].std()
    return data_frame


def n_feature_regression(chosen_feature_matrix, target_matrix, keywords):
    initial_weights = keywords['initial_weights']
    step_size = keywords['step_size']
    tolerance = keywords['tolerance']
    bias = keywords['bias']

    weights, bias = regression_gradient_descent(chosen_feature_matrix, target_matrix, initial_weights, bias, step_size,
                                                tolerance)

    return weights, bias

def get_weights_and_bias(chosen_features):
    """
    Computes the weights and bias for a general n feature model.
    :param chosen_features:  list of features to perform multiple regression on
    :return: chosen_feature_matrix, computed weights and bias via regression
    """

    
    keywords = {
        'initial_weights': np.array([.5]*len(chosen_features)),
        'step_size': 1.e-4,
        'tolerance': 1.e-10,
        'bias': 0
    }

    chosen_feature_dataframe = X_train[chosen_features]
    # chosen_feature_dataframe = normalize_features(chosen_features, chosen_feature_dataframe)
    chosen_feature_matrix = chosen_feature_dataframe.to_numpy()

    target_column = y_train
    target_matrix = target_column.to_numpy()

    train_weights, bias = n_feature_regression(chosen_feature_matrix, target_matrix, keywords)

    return chosen_feature_matrix, train_weights, bias

Logistic Regression¶

Logistic regression is a classification algorithm that predicts the probability of an instance belonging to one of two classes. It uses the logistic function to map the relationship between the input features (X) and the probability of the positive class $(P(y=1|X))$. The equation for logistic regression is:

$$(P(y=1|X)) = \sigma(z) = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-z}}$$ $$z = w_1x_1 + w_2x_2 + ... + w_nx_n + b$$

where $w_i$ is the weight asscosiated to $i^{th}$ feature.
The model estimates the optimal coefficients that minimize the difference between the predicted probabilities and the actual labels in the training data. Predictions are made by calculating the probability and applying a decision threshold.

KNN¶

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) is a simple and effective algorithm for classification and regression. It finds the K nearest neighbors to a new instance in the training data and determines its class or value based on majority voting or averaging. KNN is non-parametric and doesn't assume a specific data distribution. The choice of K is important, as it affects the model's bias-variance trade-off. KNN is easy to understand but can be computationally expensive for large datasets.

Decision Tree¶

Decision trees are intuitive machine learning models used for classification and regression. They make a sequence of decisions based on features to predict outcomes. The tree structure consists of nodes, branches, and leaves. At each node, a feature is chosen to split the data, creating child nodes. The process continues recursively until a stopping criterion is met. Leaf nodes represent predictions. Decision trees are easy to understand and handle various data types, but they can overfit. Pruning and ensemble methods can address overfitting. Decision trees are popular for their interpretability and versatility.

Q20¶

GridSearchCV is a method in scikit-learn that performs an exhaustive search over a specified parameter grid to find the best combination of hyperparameters for a given estimator. The input parameters are :

  1. estimator: The estimator object that will be used to fit the data.

  2. param_grid: A dictionary or a list of dictionaries that specifies the hyperparameters to search over.

  3. cv: The cross-validation strategy to use.

  4. scoring: The scoring metric to use to evaluate the performance of the model.

  5. n_jobs: The number of CPU cores to use for parallel processing. Setting n_jobs=-1 will use all available CPU cores.

  6. verbose: The level of verbosity during the search process. Setting verbose=1 will print progress messages during the search.

Logistic regression¶

It has several hyperparameters that can be tuned to improve the performance of the model. we use the top three here :

  1. Penalty: Logistic regression can use either L1 or L2 regularization to prevent overfitting. The penalty hyperparameter controls which type of regularization to use. L1 regularization can be used to perform feature selection by setting some coefficients to zero, while L2 regularization can be used to shrink the coefficients towards zero.

  2. C: The C hyperparameter controls the strength of the regularization. A smaller value of C results in stronger regularization, which can help prevent overfitting but may also lead to underfitting.

  3. Solver: Logistic regression can use different optimization algorithms to find the optimal coefficients. The solver hyperparameter controls which algorithm to use. The most common solvers are lbfgs, liblinear, newton-cg, sag, saga.

Q21¶

Overfitting occurs when a model becomes too specialized to the training data, memorizing noise and performing poorly on new data. It happens when the model is too complex or the training data is too limited.

Underfitting happens when a model is too simple and fails to capture the underlying patterns in the data. It leads to poor performance on both training and new data.

To address overfitting, you can increase the training data, simplify the model, or use regularization techniques. To address underfitting, you can increase the model's complexity, improve the data, or try a more advanced model.

The goal is to find the right balance between complexity and generalization to achieve optimal model performance.

Bias:
It refers to the error introduced by approximating a real-world problem with a simplified model. It represents the model's tendency to consistently predict values that are different from the true values. A high bias indicates that the model is too simplistic and unable to capture the underlying patterns in the data. It typically leads to underfitting, where the model fails to learn the training data properly and performs poorly on both the training and test data.

Variance:
It refers to the variability of model predictions for different training datasets. It quantifies how much the model's predictions fluctuate as we change the training data. A high variance indicates that the model is overly sensitive to the training data and captures noise or random fluctuations instead of the true patterns. High variance leads to overfitting, where the model performs well on the training data but fails to generalize to new, unseen data.

Random forests are an ensemble method that combines multiple decision trees to reduce variance and improve generalization but Decision Trees have more varaince and less bias because they tend to overfit with training data.

Differential Privacy¶

Q26¶

Data anonymization is the process of modifying or removing personally identifiable information (PII) from a dataset to protect the privacy of individuals. Adding noise to the dataset is one approach used in data anonymization.

The purpose of adding noise is to make it difficult to identify specific individuals within the dataset. By introducing random or perturbed values to the original data, it becomes challenging to link data points back to individuals. This helps to mitigate the risks of re-identification and inference attacks, where malicious actors try to identify individuals by analyzing patterns and relationships in the data.

While adding noise can enhance privacy and security, it is important to consider the potential trade-off with data quality and utility. The presence of noise may introduce inaccuracies or distortions in the dataset, which can affect the reliability and usefulness of the data for analysis or other applications.

To address these concerns, we use the concept of differential privacy, which is a formal framework for privacy protection. Differential privacy provides a mathematical definition and guarantees for privacy-preserving data analysis. By incorporating noise within the framework of differential privacy, it ensures a quantifiable level of privacy protection while still allowing useful analysis and insights to be derived from the data.

Q27¶

Exponential noise:
Exponential noise, also known as the Gaussian mechanism, is a commonly used noise mechanism in differential privacy. It adds random noise to the output of a computation based on the sensitivity of the computation. The sensitivity of a computation is a measure of how much the output of the computation can change when a single data point is added or removed.
In the case of exponential noise, the amount of noise added follows a Gaussian (normal) distribution. The magnitude of the noise is determined by a parameter called the privacy budget, often denoted as ε. A smaller value of ε provides stronger privacy guarantees but may result in noisier outputs. Conversely, a larger ε value provides weaker privacy guarantees but leads to less noisy outputs.

Laplace noise:
The Laplace mechanism is another noise mechanism commonly used in differential privacy. Similar to the exponential mechanism, it adds noise to the output of a computation based on the sensitivity of the computation. However, instead of following a Gaussian distribution, the noise added by the Laplace mechanism follows a Laplace distribution.

The Laplace distribution is characterized by its probability density function, which has heavy tails compared to the Gaussian distribution. This means that the Laplace mechanism is more likely to add larger amounts of noise compared to the exponential mechanism for the same privacy budget ε. The Laplace mechanism is often preferred when the sensitivity of the computation is bounded and the privacy budget ε is small, as it can provide better privacy guarantees with less noise.

Here we use the Laplace noise. As loc we use 0 and for the variance we have : $$scale = \frac{{ \text{sensitivity}}}{{\epsilon}}$$

In [ ]:
def add_noise(data, epsilon=1.0,sensitivity=1.0):
    scale = sensitivity / epsilon
    noise = np.random.laplace(0, scale=scale, size=data.shape)
    return data + noise

Gradient Boosting¶

Q29¶

Gradient Boosting :
Gradient boosting is a machine learning technique that combines multiple weak prediction models, typically decision trees, to create a strong predictive model. It sequentially builds new models to correct the mistakes made by the previous models. By combining these models, gradient boosting improves prediction accuracy and generalization. It uses gradient descent to minimize a loss function and combines predictions from multiple trees. Regularization techniques are applied to control model complexity and prevent overfitting.

Differnces :

Single Model vs. Ensemble: Decision trees are standalone models that make predictions based on a single tree structure. In contrast, gradient boosting is an ensemble method that combines multiple decision trees to create a more accurate and robust model. It sequentially builds a series of trees, where each subsequent tree corrects the mistakes made by the previous trees.

Iterative Learning: Decision trees are typically constructed in a top-down manner, recursively partitioning the data based on feature thresholds. In contrast, gradient boosting is an iterative process. It starts with an initial model and then builds subsequent models to minimize the errors made by the previous models.

Handling Complexity: Decision trees can handle complex patterns and interactions in the data. However, they're prone to overfitting, especially when the tree depth increases. Gradient boosting addresses this limitation by combining multiple shallow trees.

Regularization: Decision trees can easily grow to fit the training data precisely, potentially leading to overfitting. Gradient boosting incorporates regularization techniques to control model complexity and prevent overfitting.

Q30¶

The core idea behind XGBoost is to iteratively add new decision trees to the ensemble while minimizing a specific objective function. This objective function consists of two components: a loss function that measures the difference between predicted and actual values, and a regularization term that controls the complexity of the model and helps prevent overfitting.

To start, XGBoost initializes with a simple decision tree, such as one with only a single leaf node. This initial tree predicts the average value of the target variable for all training examples. Then, in each iteration, XGBoost calculates the gradient (slope) of the loss function with respect to the predicted values from the previous iteration. This gradient represents the direction and magnitude of the steepest descent, indicating how much the predicted values need to be adjusted to minimize the loss.

Using gradient boosting, XGBoost adds new decision trees to the ensemble to correct the mistakes made by the previous trees. Each new tree is trained to minimize the loss function by fitting the negative gradient of the loss. The learning is "additive" because each new tree is trained to gradually reduce the residual errors of the ensemble.

To ensure model generalization and prevent overfitting, XGBoost incorporates regularization techniques. It applies regularization to the structure of the trees by adding penalties to the objective function that discourage complex and over-specialized trees. This helps control the depth, width, and number of leaf nodes in each tree.

The construction of decision trees in XGBoost follows a depth-wise approach. It starts by finding the best split points at the root of the tree based on the gradients of the loss function. Then, it recursively splits the tree by evaluating the quality of splits at each level until a stopping criterion is met. After tree construction, XGBoost performs tree pruning iteratively to remove unnecessary nodes that do not contribute significantly to the overall reduction in the objective function.

Once the training process is complete, predictions are made by aggregating the predictions of all the trees in the ensemble. The final prediction is the sum of the predictions made by each individual tree, weighted by a factor determined during the training procedure.

XGBoost offers various hyperparameters that allow users to control the learning process and model complexity. These hyperparameters include the learning rate, which determines the contribution of each tree to the final prediction, and the maximum depth of the trees, which controls the tree complexity.

Q31¶

Some of the hyperparameters of the XGBClassifier are :

  1. learning_rate:
    It controls the learning rate which determines the contribution of each tree to the final ensemble. A lower value makes the model more robust by reducing the impact of each individual tree, but it may require more trees to achieve the same level of performance.

  2. max_depth:
    It sets the maximum depth of each tree in the ensemble. Deeper trees can capture more complex relationships in the data but may overfit.

  3. n_estimators:
    The number of decision trees in the ensemble. Increasing this value can make the model more accurate, but may also increase the risk of overfitting and make the model slower to train.

  4. gamma: The minimum reduction in the loss function required to make a split at a node.
